14
00:01:13,489 --> 00:01:14,950
And I spent about a year working on it.

15
00:01:14,950 --> 00:01:18,391
And that works out to about one byte per minute, you know, of effort that I spent on this game.

16
00:01:18,391 --> 00:01:21,712
You know, that was kind of the productivity of somebody back at that time in the early 80s.

17
00:01:21,712 --> 00:01:28,413
The more recent games I've been working on, in fact, even divided across, you know, 50 people over several years.

18
00:01:29,199 --> 00:01:32,159
everybody on the team is roughly generating about 100 bytes per minute.

19
00:01:32,159 --> 00:01:35,400
So we've gotten 100 times more productive in that period of time,

20
00:01:35,400 --> 00:01:38,521
which is great news, right?

21
00:01:38,521 --> 00:01:41,502
Now, Bumbling Bay was released back in 1984,

22
00:01:41,502 --> 00:01:46,883
which was, it kind of surprises me how long ago that actually seems now.

23
00:01:46,883 --> 00:01:51,044
If we think back to 1984, this is when Ma Bell was broken up, finally.

24
00:01:51,044 --> 00:01:53,225
This is, gas was a dollar and ten cents a gallon.

25
00:01:53,225 --> 00:01:56,546
The Soviets were boycotting the Olympics.

26
00:01:56,546 --> 00:01:58,026
This is back when the Soviet Union still existed.

27
00:01:59,017 --> 00:02:01,939
In the theaters, the big movies were Terminator and Ghostbusters.

28
00:02:01,939 --> 00:02:02,940
Two dollars and fifty cents to go see a movie.

29
00:02:02,940 --> 00:02:07,504
And the big things on TV, the top shows were Magnum P.I. and Dynasty.

30
00:02:07,504 --> 00:02:13,008
And this is also the year that the first portable CD player came out.

31
00:02:13,008 --> 00:02:17,412
And that was one of the things that really kind of changed the face of the way games

32
00:02:17,412 --> 00:02:19,813
were made and content delivered.

33
00:02:19,813 --> 00:02:22,275
And on that, of course, the top song that year...

34
00:02:28,175 --> 00:02:32,757
This is also way before we understood that Kevin Bacon was the center of all social networks.

35
00:02:32,757 --> 00:02:39,700
As a matter of fact, the term social network wasn't even in our lexicon back then.

36
00:02:39,700 --> 00:02:42,482
Now, 1980 is when I bought my first PC, an Apple II computer.

37
00:02:42,482 --> 00:02:46,024
Back in those days, I was actually kind of into auto racing.

38
00:02:46,024 --> 00:02:49,025
And my other big thing besides auto racing was robots.

39
00:02:49,315 --> 00:02:50,356
And that's why I bought this computer.

40
00:02:50,356 --> 00:02:51,717
It was actually one of my racing buddies,

41
00:02:51,717 --> 00:02:53,699
he had a business where he would take Apple IIs

42
00:02:53,699 --> 00:02:55,500
and kind of remake them into medical computers.

43
00:02:55,500 --> 00:02:57,341
And so he got a deal on Apple II computers,

44
00:02:57,341 --> 00:02:59,963
and he said, oh, you've got to buy one of these things.

45
00:02:59,963 --> 00:03:00,584
They're really cool.

46
00:03:00,584 --> 00:03:06,288
And so I bought one to connect to my homebrew robots at the time.

47
00:03:06,288 --> 00:03:09,110
And I was living in New York at the time,

48
00:03:09,110 --> 00:03:12,132
and I should explain that I lost my home in the Oakland Hills Fire back in 1991.

49
00:03:12,132 --> 00:03:15,395
And almost all my old prototypes and photos of Bungling Bay,

50
00:03:15,395 --> 00:03:17,517
you know, basically were burned up in that fire.

51
00:03:17,517 --> 00:03:18,317
So basically I had to...

52
00:03:18,805 --> 00:03:20,086
get a celebrity stand in here.

53
00:03:20,086 --> 00:03:25,429
So I'm having to recreate dramatically, you know, this aspect of my life.

54
00:03:25,429 --> 00:03:29,752
But anyway, as a kid, teenager, I grew up playing these elaborate board games,

55
00:03:29,752 --> 00:03:33,054
these board games like Panzer Blitz, which is a wonderful game.

56
00:03:33,054 --> 00:03:35,616
And I had this Apple II that I was kind of teaching myself to program,

57
00:03:35,616 --> 00:03:38,097
and I was living in New York and there was one computer store

58
00:03:38,097 --> 00:03:39,978
in all of New York City that I would go to.

59
00:03:39,978 --> 00:03:43,781
And at some point they started carrying games up on the wall,

60
00:03:43,781 --> 00:03:45,362
basically in Ziploc bags.

61
00:03:46,058 --> 00:03:48,500
And I started buying some of these and trying them out.

62
00:03:48,500 --> 00:03:50,501
You know, some of the earliest stuff was Bill Budge's work,

63
00:03:50,501 --> 00:03:51,521
the pinball games and stuff.

64
00:03:51,521 --> 00:03:53,422
This guy, Nasser Gabeli,

65
00:03:53,422 --> 00:03:56,283
who made these amazingly graphically intense games

66
00:03:56,283 --> 00:03:58,064
that he programmed entirely in the assembler.

67
00:03:58,064 --> 00:04:01,106
And then some of the old games that I used to play as board games

68
00:04:01,106 --> 00:04:01,706
were starting to appear.

69
00:04:01,706 --> 00:04:03,267
This is one I actually spent a lot of time with

70
00:04:03,267 --> 00:04:04,147
called Computer Ambush.

71
00:04:04,147 --> 00:04:05,948
This is actually on the box.

72
00:04:05,948 --> 00:04:08,489
It even said, programmed in AppleSoft Basic.

73
00:04:08,489 --> 00:04:10,811
And, you know, basically it was a faithful recreation

74
00:04:10,811 --> 00:04:11,531
of the board game.

75
00:04:11,531 --> 00:04:13,532
And you'd sit there and you'd make your move,

76
00:04:13,532 --> 00:04:14,672
and then you'd, you know, say, finish.

77
00:04:14,672 --> 00:04:15,493
It was a turn-based game.

78
00:04:16,103 --> 00:04:18,385
And then it would say, calculating the computer's move.

79
00:04:18,385 --> 00:04:21,366
And it would show this little progress bar that was about 40 minutes.

80
00:04:21,366 --> 00:04:23,447
And so you'd go out and get lunch, you know, and come back.

81
00:04:23,447 --> 00:04:25,648
And after lunch, maybe the computer had finished thinking about its move,

82
00:04:25,648 --> 00:04:26,609
and then you'd take your move.

83
00:04:26,609 --> 00:04:31,792
Which is about how long it took, you know, to play the real game with a real person.

84
00:04:31,792 --> 00:04:34,933
Flight Simulator was a huge kind of eye-opening experience for me,

85
00:04:34,933 --> 00:04:38,775
that for the first time there was like this really kind of consistent, microscopic little world.

86
00:04:38,775 --> 00:04:41,837
Even though it was wireframe graphics, it was incredibly primitive.

87
00:04:42,783 --> 00:04:46,124
compared to what we have nowadays, but yet the idea that there was a simulator of this

88
00:04:46,124 --> 00:04:50,446
complete little world just amazed me. And the Apple II version, the very first one,

89
00:04:50,446 --> 00:04:53,487
actually came out when you bought it, it actually, the first thing you had to do was write a

90
00:04:53,487 --> 00:04:56,929
machine language patch to get it to boot up properly on the Apple II Plus. And so the

91
00:04:56,929 --> 00:05:00,050
kind of the level of sophistication of the users was radically different than we, you

92
00:05:00,050 --> 00:05:04,172
know, think of these things now. Choplifter was another one, you know, where finally we

93
00:05:04,172 --> 00:05:08,734
were starting to get kind of arcade-like graphics. People were really starting to push the Apple

94
00:05:08,734 --> 00:05:11,375
II graphically to what it could actually do.

95
00:05:12,188 --> 00:05:16,250
And, but I basically got absorbed in learning how this computer worked. And, you know, that

96
00:05:16,250 --> 00:05:20,752
generation of 8-bit computers, one person could pretty much almost grok the whole thing.

97
00:05:20,752 --> 00:05:24,234
You could understand the interrupt structure, the hardware, the operating system, all the

98
00:05:24,234 --> 00:05:27,875
calls. And that was probably about the last time that one person could fully understand

99
00:05:27,875 --> 00:05:32,757
every operation within one of these machines. But one of the things that really sucked me

100
00:05:32,757 --> 00:05:37,239
in, you know, as I was kind of learning about this stuff, was Conway's Life. And probably

101
00:05:37,239 --> 00:05:41,181
most of you are familiar with this. You know, it's this little cellular automata world,

102
00:05:41,181 --> 00:05:42,062
deterministic.

103
00:05:42,428 --> 00:05:47,012
amazing patterns emerge from this. Complexity emerges from utter simplicity.

104
00:05:47,012 --> 00:05:52,815
And this is one of those things that can basically drive you crazy. I spent, almost lost a year

105
00:05:52,815 --> 00:05:58,279
of my life to this. And, you know, there's good and bad that came out of it, but luckily

106
00:05:58,279 --> 00:06:01,901
I pulled out of it. But, you know, one of the things that I was kind of obsessed with

107
00:06:01,901 --> 00:06:05,224
was programming this myself. And at first I programmed it in, you know, AppleSoft Basic.

108
00:06:05,224 --> 00:06:08,586
And then I taught myself Pascal and did it in Pascal because it was ten times faster.

109
00:06:09,117 --> 00:06:13,338
And then that was really the one thing that kind of got me to finally break down and learn machine language,

110
00:06:13,338 --> 00:06:17,619
which was, you know, kind of a radical thing for me compared to Pascal,

111
00:06:17,619 --> 00:06:19,540
which is highly structured, highly data-typed, etc.

112
00:06:19,540 --> 00:06:24,721
But the fact that I was able to make a live version that was a hundred times faster than my AppleSoft Basic one

113
00:06:24,721 --> 00:06:28,562
incentivized me to spend, you know, just sit down and spend two months learning how to do machine coding.

114
00:06:28,562 --> 00:06:32,823
And at that point I was basically piling up with all these games I was playing,

115
00:06:32,823 --> 00:06:36,083
and I started thinking, you know, well, maybe I should try making a game, you know,

116
00:06:36,083 --> 00:06:38,924
at least they'd be tax-deductible then, all the stuff I buy from my computer.

117
00:06:39,466 --> 00:06:45,650
And so it was almost more of a whim, that I'm just going to try programming a game that I've learned, you know, to program and that I enjoy games.

118
00:06:45,650 --> 00:06:48,452
And it really kind of came down to, you know, what kind of game am I going to do?

119
00:06:48,452 --> 00:06:53,355
Now at that time, also, a lot of the people in the Apple II were really kind of on their second and third generation games.

120
00:06:53,355 --> 00:06:57,158
They really had figured out kind of how to exploit that hardware to the fullest.

121
00:06:57,158 --> 00:06:59,679
And so I was kind of a little behind the pack on that one.

122
00:06:59,679 --> 00:07:02,461
But right around that time, the Commodore 64 was just coming out to market.

123
00:07:02,461 --> 00:07:03,722
And so I thought, well, I have an idea.

124
00:07:03,722 --> 00:07:07,805
I'll just kind of buy one of these new computers and learn it as quickly as I can.

125
00:07:08,440 --> 00:07:10,502
and work on that machine. That way it's more of a level playing field.

126
00:07:10,502 --> 00:07:13,343
So I did. I went out and bought a shiny new Commodore 64.

127
00:07:13,343 --> 00:07:15,364
I paid full retail price of $600 for it.

128
00:07:15,364 --> 00:07:18,346
Very shortly afterwards it dropped to about $300

129
00:07:18,346 --> 00:07:20,747
and that's when it really just kind of skyrocketed, the penetration of it.

130
00:07:20,747 --> 00:07:24,730
And basically the only technical information that came with it

131
00:07:24,730 --> 00:07:26,851
was the programmer's reference guide.

132
00:07:26,851 --> 00:07:28,712
And basically I absorbed that book.

133
00:07:28,712 --> 00:07:32,994
I just spent day after day reading and absorbing and experimenting with this computer.

134
00:07:32,994 --> 00:07:34,735
Now what made the Commodore 64 kind of special,

135
00:07:34,735 --> 00:07:38,077
relative to the Apple II, were these two chips inside of it, Vic and Sid.

136
00:07:38,850 --> 00:07:43,494
VIC was the Video Interface Controller, SID was the Sound Interface Device. And these,

137
00:07:43,494 --> 00:07:46,936
you know, basically were very powerful chips designed by Motorola that allowed the Commodore

138
00:07:46,936 --> 00:07:51,700
to do really cool graphic and sound things that the Apple II really couldn't do. Basically,

139
00:07:51,700 --> 00:07:55,203
you kind of interacted with these chips through peaks and pokes, which were pretty aptly named

140
00:07:55,203 --> 00:07:58,886
because while the VIC was pretty logical, and you could read the manual and it would

141
00:07:58,886 --> 00:08:02,409
pretty much, you know, do what it said, the SID chip was totally unpredictable. And so

142
00:08:02,409 --> 00:08:05,531
pretty much all you did as a programmer was sit there and poke the thing over and over

143
00:08:05,531 --> 00:08:07,133
and see what kind of sounds it would make.

144
00:08:07,425 --> 00:08:11,148
It was totally experimental, you know, and just basically it was totally trial and error,

145
00:08:11,148 --> 00:08:15,712
empirical, let's see how to make, you know, let's say I'm going to poke it a million times.

146
00:08:15,712 --> 00:08:22,277
Now on the VIC chip, you know, one of the kind of cool features of the Commodore that attracted my attention right off the bat was the idea that you could redefine the character set,

147
00:08:22,277 --> 00:08:29,703
and then smoothly scroll that around on the screen, which kind of gave you the ability to do these smooth scrolling worlds that was very difficult to do on the Apple.

148
00:08:29,703 --> 00:08:36,549
You know, the Apple you basically had to implement it as a bitmap, and it wasn't fast enough, even with the 1 megahertz 6502, to move that much data very smoothly.

149
00:08:37,328 --> 00:08:42,450
So what I did is I had actually been programming on my Apple II for quite a while, and there

150
00:08:42,450 --> 00:08:45,911
were some really good tools on the Apple II. At the time when the Commodore first came

151
00:08:45,911 --> 00:08:49,772
out, the tools really sucked. You know, the compilers were slow, the disk drive was slow.

152
00:08:49,772 --> 00:08:53,613
And I had a bright idea, which is I'm going to do all my programming on the Apple II,

153
00:08:53,613 --> 00:08:57,074
and then I'm going to dump it into the Commodore. So I actually wrote, you know, a little machine

154
00:08:57,074 --> 00:09:00,515
language routine on each end, built a hardware interface between the two, so I could do all

155
00:09:00,515 --> 00:09:03,816
of my programming on the Apple II, press a button, it would instantly spit that program

156
00:09:03,816 --> 00:09:05,217
into Commodore's memory and start running.

157
00:09:05,688 --> 00:09:07,349
So it made for a very quick iteration cycle,

158
00:09:07,349 --> 00:09:09,371
and so I was able to learn the machine very rapidly

159
00:09:09,371 --> 00:09:11,012
and keep all of my development tools on the Apple II.

160
00:09:11,012 --> 00:09:13,655
But still, I was kind of left with, you know,

161
00:09:13,655 --> 00:09:15,857
what kind of game do I want to make here?

162
00:09:15,857 --> 00:09:18,499
And ever since I was a little kid, I loved helicopters,

163
00:09:18,499 --> 00:09:21,001
you know, and right off the bat, it was like,

164
00:09:21,001 --> 00:09:22,402
okay, helicopters, helicopters.

165
00:09:22,402 --> 00:09:24,184
I remember as a young kid,

166
00:09:24,184 --> 00:09:26,186
probably my first interaction with a helicopter

167
00:09:26,186 --> 00:09:27,987
was my dad took me to a state fair,

168
00:09:27,987 --> 00:09:30,249
and they had helicopter rides in an old Bell 47.

169
00:09:30,249 --> 00:09:32,591
And I remember I was probably maybe four or five years old.

170
00:09:32,591 --> 00:09:33,732
We went up in a helicopter ride.

171
00:09:34,096 --> 00:09:36,957
and it was like the coolest thing in the world.

172
00:09:36,957 --> 00:09:40,738
So later, you know, one of my favorite TV shows was this,

173
00:09:40,738 --> 00:09:43,559
Mutual of Omaha's Wildlife Kingdom.

174
00:09:43,559 --> 00:09:46,741
Marlon Perkins was this guy, and he would go around various places in the world

175
00:09:46,741 --> 00:09:48,461
and kind of study endangered animals.

176
00:09:48,461 --> 00:09:49,442
He had this sidekick, I forgot his name.

177
00:09:49,442 --> 00:09:52,343
But no matter what was happening, no matter what the animal was,

178
00:09:52,343 --> 00:09:54,884
it seemed to me like almost every single episode

179
00:09:54,884 --> 00:09:57,485
eventually resolved into them chasing a herd with a helicopter

180
00:09:57,485 --> 00:09:59,405
and tranquilizing something.

181
00:09:59,758 --> 00:10:01,339
And so you'd watch this whole show about the animals,

182
00:10:01,339 --> 00:10:02,500
oh, the poor baboons or whatever,

183
00:10:02,500 --> 00:10:04,041
but eventually they're chasing a herd of them

184
00:10:04,041 --> 00:10:06,662
with a helicopter and cheating at them.

185
00:10:06,662 --> 00:10:08,903
But, so that was like kind of the money shot for this show.

186
00:10:08,903 --> 00:10:12,125
But, and so I, you know, I've just ever since then

187
00:10:12,125 --> 00:10:14,266
loved helicopters of every type, civilian, military, etc.

188
00:10:14,266 --> 00:10:18,068
So I kind of knew that I wanted this game to be about helicopters.

189
00:10:18,068 --> 00:10:21,630
You know, now based upon kind of my interaction with Conway's life

190
00:10:21,630 --> 00:10:23,631
and cellular automaton and all that,

191
00:10:23,631 --> 00:10:25,252
I knew I also wanted in this game

192
00:10:25,252 --> 00:10:28,373
there to be this kind of intricate, kind of clock-like world.

193
00:10:29,159 --> 00:10:31,320
I've always enjoyed kind of things like this,

194
00:10:31,320 --> 00:10:33,801
Ori's and things where they were kind of simulating

195
00:10:33,801 --> 00:10:35,302
world in very mechanistic fashion,

196
00:10:35,302 --> 00:10:38,044
very precise little things that have a lot of

197
00:10:38,044 --> 00:10:40,485
kind of unpredictable complexity emerging from them.

198
00:10:40,485 --> 00:10:41,666
So that was kind of like my second thing.

199
00:10:41,666 --> 00:10:43,447
It's about helicopters and there's kind of this

200
00:10:43,447 --> 00:10:45,428
clock-like little world of things going on inside of it.

201
00:10:45,428 --> 00:10:47,289
And the last one was, you know,

202
00:10:47,289 --> 00:10:48,530
the games I've been playing on the Apple II,

203
00:10:48,530 --> 00:10:50,731
you know, really were very simple little worlds.

204
00:10:50,731 --> 00:10:52,272
You were, you know, continuously scrolling

205
00:10:52,272 --> 00:10:53,693
back and forth or whatever.

206
00:10:53,693 --> 00:10:54,913
And I wanted a game where basically

207
00:10:54,913 --> 00:10:56,254
the world was large enough to get lost in.

208
00:10:57,015 --> 00:11:01,056
And that's, you know, basically what I wanted to accomplish with this, you know, smooth scrolling.

209
00:11:01,056 --> 00:11:06,557
I wanted to build a very large world that I could potentially kind of get lost in and feel like it was that large.

210
00:11:06,557 --> 00:11:10,238
So, going down this path, I kind of wrote two programs on the Commodore.

211
00:11:10,238 --> 00:11:11,858
One was Chedit and the other was Wedit.

212
00:11:11,858 --> 00:11:16,599
Chedit was a character editor, and this is what I would actually use to create custom characters.

213
00:11:16,599 --> 00:11:21,139
On the Commodore, you could redefine the character set and build graphic characters at fairly low resolution.

214
00:11:21,139 --> 00:11:21,840
It was like 4 by 8.

215
00:11:21,840 --> 00:11:24,360
And they had to be one of, you know, four of 16 colors.

216
00:11:24,360 --> 00:11:26,440
This is the entire palette on the Commodore.

217
00:11:26,855 --> 00:11:30,556
and you had to pick your four favorite colors and kind of use those. And so the whole background

218
00:11:30,556 --> 00:11:34,057
was kind of built out of those four colors. Now, Wettit was actually a program that allowed

219
00:11:34,057 --> 00:11:38,179
me to now scroll around this large world and place these custom characters in little patterns,

220
00:11:38,179 --> 00:11:41,700
just kind of dropping down tiles. And this is basically how I built the world for Raid

221
00:11:41,700 --> 00:11:45,682
on Mungling Bay. And in fact, later, after I finished Raid on Mungling Bay, it was Wettit

222
00:11:45,682 --> 00:11:49,543
that kind of eventually evolved into SimCity. I was having so much fun kind of like building

223
00:11:49,543 --> 00:11:52,745
these little worlds in Wettit that I started adding more and more features to it and making

224
00:11:52,745 --> 00:11:55,826
it a little bit more automatic and a little bit kind of more satisfying.

225
00:11:57,152 --> 00:12:01,534
Now, back in those days, you know, we actually had memory maps, where we actually were very

226
00:12:01,534 --> 00:12:05,237
aware of, you know, where all the memory was in the machine, what we were doing with it.

227
00:12:05,237 --> 00:12:08,639
We didn't really allocate memory so much as we usurped it. You know, you just kind of

228
00:12:08,639 --> 00:12:11,821
came in and said, I'm using that memory, and that memory, and that memory. The Commodore

229
00:12:11,821 --> 00:12:14,722
is kind of nice because you could basically map out all the ROM that you didn't need,

230
00:12:14,722 --> 00:12:18,705
which is mostly like the basic and the kernel and all that kind of stuff. And the one part

231
00:12:18,705 --> 00:12:21,747
you didn't really want to use was this one 4K slice over here, which is where Vic and

232
00:12:21,747 --> 00:12:24,829
Sid lived, and you're using them all the time. But otherwise, we basically had, you know,

233
00:12:24,829 --> 00:12:26,310
about 60K free to kind of work with.

234
00:12:26,939 --> 00:12:29,340
And we would build these elaborate memory maps.

235
00:12:29,340 --> 00:12:31,461
Pretty much this is standard the way games were programmed back then.

236
00:12:31,461 --> 00:12:34,183
And you knew exactly where every piece of code was, every piece of data,

237
00:12:34,183 --> 00:12:36,124
and it didn't move, because you put it there.

238
00:12:36,124 --> 00:12:37,404
And if you needed to put something new in there,

239
00:12:37,404 --> 00:12:39,405
you would basically find a little chunk, you'd move things around,

240
00:12:39,405 --> 00:12:40,686
and you'd kind of update it on the map.

241
00:12:40,686 --> 00:12:42,807
And so this is a continually evolving little map.

242
00:12:42,807 --> 00:12:46,749
And this is exactly the kind of way we thought about it.

243
00:12:46,749 --> 00:12:49,050
It was very to-the-metal programming.

244
00:12:49,050 --> 00:12:52,331
To the point where memory was this incredible commodity.

245
00:12:52,331 --> 00:12:54,473
Toward the end of this project,

246
00:12:54,473 --> 00:12:56,333
a lot of other people were working the same way.

247
00:12:56,754 --> 00:13:00,636
You know, you'd need five bytes or six bytes to do one cool little thing, and so you'd

248
00:13:00,636 --> 00:13:04,098
go scrounging around in memory. Even though I filled up every last byte in that machine,

249
00:13:04,098 --> 00:13:07,880
you'd start using tricks. Like, one trick was looking for a pair of JSR RTS pair like

250
00:13:07,880 --> 00:13:12,623
this, which is actually jumping to a subroutine, and then when it comes back from that subroutine,

251
00:13:12,623 --> 00:13:16,205
it's returning back from the outer subroutine. You could replace that with a jump, in which

252
00:13:16,205 --> 00:13:20,627
case the RTS at the bottom of the first subroutine jumps you all the way back out, and you end

253
00:13:20,627 --> 00:13:24,869
up saving exactly one byte. So if you can find five of these pairs, you can actually

254
00:13:24,869 --> 00:13:25,770
get five bytes back.

255
00:13:26,308 --> 00:13:29,490
And we actually spent time doing this, hunting through the code, looking for little tricks

256
00:13:29,490 --> 00:13:33,052
like this, you know, because I need 10 bytes now and 5 bytes here. And that's the, you

257
00:13:33,052 --> 00:13:35,993
know, amount to which we were utilizing all the memory in these machines. It was just

258
00:13:35,993 --> 00:13:40,015
kind of ridiculous. In fact, kind of after that, you know, second, third generation computers

259
00:13:40,015 --> 00:13:43,596
after that, I'd be talking to programmers and they'd be, you know, allocating a 10-byte

260
00:13:43,596 --> 00:13:47,518
record that we needed for whatever reason. But they said, oh, I can only allocate this

261
00:13:47,518 --> 00:13:51,120
as a 256-byte chunk. And it's like, oh, my God, you're wasting 240 bytes? You know, it's

262
00:13:51,120 --> 00:13:55,042
almost like my grandparents that grew up in the Depression telling me about wasting food

263
00:13:55,042 --> 00:13:55,422
or something.

264
00:13:56,218 --> 00:13:57,639
That's how I'd feel talking to these programmers.

265
00:13:57,639 --> 00:13:59,980
And it took me a while to kind of get out of that mindset.

266
00:13:59,980 --> 00:14:01,021
OK, memory's cheap. Memory's cheap.

267
00:14:01,021 --> 00:14:03,062
You know, I had to keep repeating that to myself.

268
00:14:03,062 --> 00:14:05,403
So back to the world.

269
00:14:05,403 --> 00:14:09,585
So basically, I started drawing out this little world of islands and water.

270
00:14:09,585 --> 00:14:13,067
And this is the world I wanted to kind of build the game around.

271
00:14:13,067 --> 00:14:16,948
This is actually kind of a zoomed out version of what became the eventual world.

272
00:14:16,948 --> 00:14:19,209
This is about a hundred screens of data.

273
00:14:19,209 --> 00:14:22,791
So basically one screen was about that large, you know, as you're playing the game.

274
00:14:22,791 --> 00:14:24,852
And the idea is that as you're flying this helicopter around...

275
00:14:25,190 --> 00:14:29,373
this little thing is kind of panning over the map very smoothly and that was basically

276
00:14:29,373 --> 00:14:32,635
my core idea for how this game would work. I'm flying a helicopter over this world, it's

277
00:14:32,635 --> 00:14:35,798
going to scroll around smoothly and things will be coming after you. You know, that was

278
00:14:35,798 --> 00:14:40,121
about as deeply as I'd thought it out at that point. Now, I kind of got into this prototype

279
00:14:40,121 --> 00:14:45,045
phase where I was scrolling around this little world with my helicopter and I had little

280
00:14:45,045 --> 00:14:47,847
airplanes kind of chasing me down, firing missiles at me. You know, that was basically

281
00:14:47,847 --> 00:14:51,590
the game. And I had moved to California at that time and

282
00:14:51,858 --> 00:14:55,702
you know, basically the Bay Area, and this is kind of like the center of the computer gaming universe at that time.

283
00:14:55,702 --> 00:14:57,563
About half the computer gaming companies were in the Bay Area.

284
00:14:57,563 --> 00:15:02,807
And there were about five, I don't even remember, like, LunaSoft and a few others.

285
00:15:02,807 --> 00:15:05,310
And I ended up just kind of going to all the ones in the Bay Area,

286
00:15:05,310 --> 00:15:08,692
kind of showing them my little prototype, saying, you know, what do you think of this game?

287
00:15:08,692 --> 00:15:10,374
And one of the ones I went to was Brøderbund.

288
00:15:10,374 --> 00:15:12,756
You know, this was way, way back in the early days.

289
00:15:12,756 --> 00:15:17,219
I met the Carlstons, Doug and Gary Carlston, and later Kathy joined a few years later.

290
00:15:17,219 --> 00:15:20,642
But at that time, Brøderbund Software was 17 people.

291
00:15:21,282 --> 00:15:25,663
They were running it actually out of an old liquor store in San Rafael that they had taken over.

292
00:15:25,663 --> 00:15:30,064
And it was really cute because in the back there was this freezer door and that's where the programmers lived.

293
00:15:30,064 --> 00:15:33,764
There were like five programmers and the programmers didn't like light, you know,

294
00:15:33,764 --> 00:15:36,745
and they'd open this giant freezer door and there'd be five programmers sitting back there.

295
00:15:36,745 --> 00:15:38,605
They'd turn the freezer off, of course.

296
00:15:38,605 --> 00:15:43,546
But it was just like so quaint and, you know, there's these wonderful, you know,

297
00:15:43,546 --> 00:15:45,666
kind of family-run business in a way.

298
00:15:45,666 --> 00:15:49,507
You know, they're kind of of Swedish descent, you know, these kind of wonderful, you know,

299
00:15:49,507 --> 00:15:50,507
peace-loving, very...

300
00:15:51,809 --> 00:15:57,632
Very nice people, and they were kind of horrified actually later to learn they had named their company after an extremist African apartheid group.

301
00:15:57,632 --> 00:16:05,517
But at any rate, other people I had met at Brøderbund, you know, of the 17, you know, Gene Portwood, who passed away about 10 years ago,

302
00:16:05,517 --> 00:16:09,879
was just a wonderful guy. He was really my first project manager on Mungling Bay.

303
00:16:09,879 --> 00:16:14,021
He was a former Disney animator. He was the oldest guy at Brøderbund by far.

304
00:16:14,021 --> 00:16:17,823
You know, he was like in his 50s and everybody else was, you know, young 20-somethings.

305
00:16:17,823 --> 00:16:21,725
So he was this grizzled old veteran that was just, you know, incorrigible.

306
00:16:22,315 --> 00:16:25,037
Later, his partner, Lauren Elliott, joined with him,

307
00:16:25,037 --> 00:16:27,199
and they both were working with me on both, you know,

308
00:16:27,199 --> 00:16:29,180
Random Bungling Bay and on later Sim City.

309
00:16:29,180 --> 00:16:31,202
These are the two guys that kind of later went off

310
00:16:31,202 --> 00:16:32,863
to go invent Carmen Sandiego

311
00:16:32,863 --> 00:16:34,044
and turn that into a giant hit.

312
00:16:34,044 --> 00:16:36,546
But the other person at Brøderbund that was kind of

313
00:16:36,546 --> 00:16:38,327
a huge influence on Random Bungling Bay

314
00:16:38,327 --> 00:16:40,729
was a guy named Alan Weiss, who was, you know,

315
00:16:40,729 --> 00:16:42,050
ran the testing group at Brøderbund.

316
00:16:42,050 --> 00:16:44,052
The testing group, you know, was really three people

317
00:16:44,052 --> 00:16:46,314
or something like that, you know, three part-time people

318
00:16:46,314 --> 00:16:47,355
and then Alan full-time.

319
00:16:47,355 --> 00:16:50,477
So Alan is probably the only person that's played

320
00:16:51,050 --> 00:16:53,611
And he would sit there and give me just like this great feedback about,

321
00:16:53,611 --> 00:16:55,712
oh, I think this is too hard, you know, we need to adjust this,

322
00:16:55,712 --> 00:16:56,312
that's too fast, etc.

323
00:16:56,312 --> 00:17:03,135
But really the person that probably gave me the most advice was Gary Carlston.

324
00:17:03,135 --> 00:17:05,857
Gary would spend so much time with me just talking about the market

325
00:17:05,857 --> 00:17:07,858
and where things were going and entertainment

326
00:17:07,858 --> 00:17:09,719
and stuff he learned about business.

327
00:17:09,719 --> 00:17:12,680
You know, I really felt like Gary Carlston was kind of my mentor for business.

328
00:17:12,680 --> 00:17:15,841
And I just always appreciated the time he sat down, you know,

329
00:17:15,841 --> 00:17:18,783
for no apparent reason, he would just, you know, spend hours kind of...

330
00:17:19,140 --> 00:17:21,222
telling me the way he saw the market developing,

331
00:17:21,222 --> 00:17:23,844
or the way he thought business should be run.

332
00:17:23,844 --> 00:17:27,167
Just a wonderful kind of learning experience,

333
00:17:27,167 --> 00:17:29,429
and I owe Gary a deep debt of gratitude

334
00:17:29,429 --> 00:17:32,291
for that time that he spent with me.

335
00:17:32,291 --> 00:17:33,092
But back to the game.

336
00:17:33,092 --> 00:17:34,973
So at that point, we were starting to think,

337
00:17:34,973 --> 00:17:37,235
okay, we're going to start populating this world with targets.

338
00:17:37,235 --> 00:17:39,437
And at first, basically we were going to put down factories.

339
00:17:39,437 --> 00:17:41,318
And so Bungling Bay had six factories

340
00:17:41,318 --> 00:17:42,319
spread across these islands.

341
00:17:42,319 --> 00:17:45,322
Now, basically I wanted this clockwork universe

342
00:17:45,322 --> 00:17:46,763
that we're going to build here.

343
00:17:47,172 --> 00:17:51,155
And so I had this idea in my mind that there were resources distributed out in this world

344
00:17:51,155 --> 00:17:54,858
that somehow the bungling empire, and we'll get into that later, is collecting.

345
00:17:54,858 --> 00:17:57,340
And they actually collect this with little boats that actually drive around,

346
00:17:57,340 --> 00:17:59,622
and they actually go on these pre-programmed circuits,

347
00:17:59,622 --> 00:18:01,584
and they cycle back to little port areas.

348
00:18:01,584 --> 00:18:04,567
And they take these resources to these little tanks,

349
00:18:04,567 --> 00:18:07,589
which then carry the resources to the factories.

350
00:18:07,589 --> 00:18:12,273
And this is, you know, basically the underlying infrastructure of the bungling war machine.

351
00:18:13,076 --> 00:18:16,438
On top of that, we wanted to build their defensive networks.

352
00:18:16,438 --> 00:18:20,481
And so they have anti-aircraft guns spread out across the islands,

353
00:18:20,481 --> 00:18:21,281
radar dishes.

354
00:18:21,281 --> 00:18:26,585
The radar dishes actually call in airstrikes from two air bases that are in the world.

355
00:18:26,585 --> 00:18:29,106
And lastly, this battleship, which is kind of a long-term timer.

356
00:18:29,106 --> 00:18:31,588
At some point, the battleship is being constructed during the game.

357
00:18:31,588 --> 00:18:34,970
As you start bombing more factories, the construction accelerates.

358
00:18:34,970 --> 00:18:37,892
Once it's completed, it actually steams out a port toward your carrier,

359
00:18:37,892 --> 00:18:39,273
which is sailing up and down this world.

360
00:18:39,273 --> 00:18:41,194
And if it ever gets to the carrier, you lose the carrier.

361
00:18:41,842 --> 00:18:44,302
and that's kind of part of the tension of the game.

362
00:18:44,302 --> 00:18:46,422
So basically we have this resource model

363
00:18:46,422 --> 00:18:48,943
where resources are being collected out in the water,

364
00:18:48,943 --> 00:18:50,303
brought by little boats, these little tanks,

365
00:18:50,303 --> 00:18:51,503
to the factories.

366
00:18:51,503 --> 00:18:53,584
Those resources are being spent on the defenses,

367
00:18:53,584 --> 00:18:54,744
and there's a priority system,

368
00:18:54,744 --> 00:18:57,524
where first they will rebuild any local anti-aircraft guns,

369
00:18:57,524 --> 00:18:59,124
then radar dishes,

370
00:18:59,124 --> 00:19:01,105
then any fighter jets or bombers,

371
00:19:01,105 --> 00:19:03,165
then the tanks, and lastly the boats.

372
00:19:03,165 --> 00:19:05,146
So there's basically a repair priority

373
00:19:05,146 --> 00:19:06,846
and a resource flow into that repair priority.

374
00:19:06,846 --> 00:19:09,786
And this is the basic little mechanism of this world,

375
00:19:09,786 --> 00:19:11,387
this game, how it operated.

376
00:19:12,732 --> 00:19:13,513
Oh, okay.

377
00:19:13,513 --> 00:19:24,362
So, flight diversion.

378
00:19:24,362 --> 00:19:29,767
Believe me, it is hard to talk for an hour about a game that you can finish in ten minutes.

379
00:19:29,767 --> 00:19:32,429
So I did a little padding here.

380
00:19:32,429 --> 00:19:37,934
Outside of Moscow, there's this museum, the Museum of Cosmonautics.

381
00:19:37,934 --> 00:19:40,136
This is actually the roof of the museum.

382
00:19:40,136 --> 00:19:41,337
The museum's underneath this.

383
00:19:41,805 --> 00:19:46,849
And there's a park outside of this where they basically have statues of the major heroes

384
00:19:46,849 --> 00:19:48,310
of the Soviet space program.

385
00:19:48,310 --> 00:19:53,454
And the Soviet space program really has four consistent heroes that they always have statues

386
00:19:53,454 --> 00:19:54,795
of and monuments to.

387
00:19:54,795 --> 00:19:59,499
One was Sergei Korolev, the chief designer, who was basically their chief engineer that

388
00:19:59,499 --> 00:20:01,261
architected their space program.

389
00:20:01,261 --> 00:20:04,223
Yuri Gagarin, of course, the first man in space.

390
00:20:04,223 --> 00:20:07,025
Valentina Tereshkova, the first woman in space.

391
00:20:07,025 --> 00:20:10,628
And lastly, Alexei Leonov, who was the first guy to ever walk in space.

392
00:20:11,927 --> 00:20:15,549
Basically, I'm going to focus today on the Russian Space Minute on this last guy, Alexei Leonov.

393
00:20:15,549 --> 00:20:22,033
Now, in addition to being the first guy to walk in space, he was also the commander of the Apollo-Soyuz test project,

394
00:20:22,033 --> 00:20:25,155
you know, the first time that an American and Soviet spacecraft had docked in orbit.

395
00:20:25,155 --> 00:20:27,717
And he was training to be the first cosmonaut on the Moon,

396
00:20:27,717 --> 00:20:30,178
back when the Soviets were actually pursuing their lunar program.

397
00:20:30,178 --> 00:20:33,481
He actually flew on the Vostok 2, or Voskhod 2, excuse me,

398
00:20:33,481 --> 00:20:36,923
which was a slight modification of the Vostok.

399
00:20:36,923 --> 00:20:39,965
He made the first six Soviet spaceflights.

400
00:20:39,965 --> 00:20:41,806
The one with Yuri Gagarin was the first one.

401
00:20:42,234 --> 00:20:46,137
were all in a Vostok. And it was a one-person capsule. And the reason it was a one-person

402
00:20:46,137 --> 00:20:50,260
capsule was that when it was coming down from orbit, they didn't really have the capability

403
00:20:50,260 --> 00:20:54,323
to have a soft landing. This thing smashed into the earth really, really hard. And what

404
00:20:54,323 --> 00:20:57,486
most people didn't know, they didn't know back then, and it wasn't until many years

405
00:20:57,486 --> 00:21:02,449
later they found out, was that he was actually ejecting from the capsule on its way through

406
00:21:02,449 --> 00:21:06,452
reentry. So when the capsule was coming through about 30,000 feet in the air, what would happen

407
00:21:06,452 --> 00:21:11,196
is this ejection seat would fire him out of the capsule, and it was a very elaborate ejection

408
00:21:11,196 --> 00:21:12,077
seat.

409
00:21:12,916 --> 00:21:16,758
After that came down to about 10,000 feet, he would actually jump out of that and then

410
00:21:16,758 --> 00:21:17,838
open a parachute.

411
00:21:17,838 --> 00:21:21,660
So the first six cosmonauts that went into orbit were actually landing by parachute while

412
00:21:21,660 --> 00:21:24,702
their spacecraft crashed about 10 kilometers away.

413
00:21:24,702 --> 00:21:27,683
This ejection thing was just amazingly complicated.

414
00:21:27,683 --> 00:21:31,024
I actually got to talk to one of the engineers who designed it.

415
00:21:31,024 --> 00:21:33,686
And the amount of redundancies and fail-safes in this thing were extraordinary.

416
00:21:33,686 --> 00:21:34,486
It was all mechanical.

417
00:21:34,486 --> 00:21:37,728
They basically had mechanical computers embedded in this thing to detect if it was landing

418
00:21:37,728 --> 00:21:39,468
on water or if the cosmonaut was knocked out.

419
00:21:39,468 --> 00:21:42,030
They had no idea what the state of the cosmonaut would be coming back from orbit.

420
00:21:42,532 --> 00:21:45,273
So they had all these automatic things that would push him out of the seat and cause this

421
00:21:45,273 --> 00:21:46,813
parachute to open if he was unconscious.

422
00:21:46,813 --> 00:21:49,434
And when he was explaining all this stuff to me, I was kind of asking him, how do you

423
00:21:49,434 --> 00:21:49,774
test this?

424
00:21:49,774 --> 00:21:52,295
And this seat was also used for launch aborts.

425
00:21:52,295 --> 00:21:55,256
Basically if the rocket was about to blow up on the launch pad, they could fire them

426
00:21:55,256 --> 00:21:58,518
out of this and it would basically, the idea is it could safely land the cosmonaut from

427
00:21:58,518 --> 00:21:59,018
the launch pad.

428
00:21:59,018 --> 00:22:03,059
And he said they built a tower, same height as the launch pad, as the rocket on the launch

429
00:22:03,059 --> 00:22:06,961
pad, and they built a launcher that would basically, you know, test this thing and find

430
00:22:06,961 --> 00:22:09,182
out how many of the crash dummies survived this.

431
00:22:09,630 --> 00:22:12,071
And I asked him how many, you know, did they have to do to get it right?

432
00:22:12,071 --> 00:22:17,474
And he said, by the time they finished, there was this giant pile of prototypes underneath this launch apparatus.

433
00:22:17,474 --> 00:22:21,055
But at any rate, so the Voskhod, finally they got the landing right.

434
00:22:21,055 --> 00:22:24,697
They actually had retrorockets that would fire before the capsule landed.

435
00:22:24,697 --> 00:22:27,438
And so the next flight, which is now labeled the Voskhod 1,

436
00:22:27,438 --> 00:22:30,420
they crammed three cosmonauts just to see if they could do it.

437
00:22:30,420 --> 00:22:31,620
And they made a successful flight.

438
00:22:31,620 --> 00:22:33,701
They just basically went up, did a few orbits, and came down.

439
00:22:33,701 --> 00:22:35,882
And it was the first flight with more than one person in space.

440
00:22:35,882 --> 00:22:39,084
And it was the next Voskhod that Alexei went up on, the Voskhod 2.

441
00:22:39,572 --> 00:22:41,353
And what they did is they took out one of the passengers,

442
00:22:41,353 --> 00:22:44,734
and they used that extra room to attach this bizarre airlock device

443
00:22:44,734 --> 00:22:46,915
onto the side of the capsule.

444
00:22:46,915 --> 00:22:48,996
What it was, it was an inflatable airlock.

445
00:22:48,996 --> 00:22:51,136
They would get up in this space, inflate this thing,

446
00:22:51,136 --> 00:22:53,677
and it would pop out like a balloon, basically.

447
00:22:53,677 --> 00:22:55,318
This is actually a ground prototype of it.

448
00:22:55,318 --> 00:22:58,939
And the cosmonaut would climb inside of this thing,

449
00:22:58,939 --> 00:23:00,520
close the hatch, and then they would decompress it.

450
00:23:00,520 --> 00:23:03,161
They couldn't decompress their entire cabin like they did on Gemini,

451
00:23:03,161 --> 00:23:04,802
because all their electronics...

452
00:23:05,250 --> 00:23:07,651
were basically very rudimentary air-cooled electronics.

453
00:23:07,651 --> 00:23:09,531
And the electronics would have overheated almost instantly

454
00:23:09,531 --> 00:23:11,532
had they depressurized the capsule.

455
00:23:11,532 --> 00:23:13,633
But anyway, that was kind of the plan.

456
00:23:13,633 --> 00:23:15,754
And so they launched in March 1965.

457
00:23:15,754 --> 00:23:18,875
They went up, you know, everything was pretty much normal.

458
00:23:18,875 --> 00:23:21,176
Alexei kind of got in the airlock, depressurized,

459
00:23:21,176 --> 00:23:21,977
got out into space.

460
00:23:21,977 --> 00:23:23,477
As soon as he got into space,

461
00:23:23,477 --> 00:23:25,118
two very unexpected things happened.

462
00:23:25,118 --> 00:23:27,239
Now, first of all, realize that nobody had ever done this before

463
00:23:27,239 --> 00:23:28,439
and they were only kind of guessing

464
00:23:28,439 --> 00:23:29,380
what the dynamics might be.

465
00:23:29,380 --> 00:23:30,720
They hadn't really thought it through that much.

466
00:23:30,720 --> 00:23:33,962
The first thing is that his suit inflated like a balloon.

467
00:23:34,420 --> 00:23:37,201
they hadn't really considered the fact that he was in a vacuum, that he was full of air.

468
00:23:37,201 --> 00:23:39,942
The second thing is that he started overheating.

469
00:23:39,942 --> 00:23:44,324
This is about the first and only EVA suit that didn't have an integral cooling unit

470
00:23:44,324 --> 00:23:45,404
for the astronaut.

471
00:23:45,404 --> 00:23:49,205
All the astronauts now have this woven set of tubes that go across their body and circulate

472
00:23:49,205 --> 00:23:53,126
air to cool them because the amount of solar radiation you're receiving is tremendous.

473
00:23:53,126 --> 00:23:58,048
And so within a few minutes, you know, Alexei was basically out here like this, overheating,

474
00:23:58,048 --> 00:24:02,950
sweat was piling up in his space suit, and he realized he better get back in fast.

475
00:24:03,175 --> 00:24:06,456
He managed to just barely kind of squeeze back into the airlock,

476
00:24:06,456 --> 00:24:08,477
but he couldn't get in feet first the way he was supposed to.

477
00:24:08,477 --> 00:24:11,437
He had to get in head first, the opposite way, which was totally unplanned.

478
00:24:11,437 --> 00:24:15,118
You know, at this point, he had actually lost several pounds from sweat,

479
00:24:15,118 --> 00:24:17,279
and it was pooling up around him inside the spacesuit.

480
00:24:17,279 --> 00:24:19,099
But he did manage to get in the airlock,

481
00:24:19,099 --> 00:24:22,780
but the only way to close the hatch was to turn around inside that inflatable tube.

482
00:24:22,780 --> 00:24:24,160
And he, you know, tried as he could.

483
00:24:24,160 --> 00:24:28,201
He could not actually maneuver his body to turn around and do a 180 inside the tube.

484
00:24:28,201 --> 00:24:30,962
So his last kind of hope was to actually let air out of his suit.

485
00:24:31,357 --> 00:24:33,278
And so he actually started bleeding air out of his suit

486
00:24:33,278 --> 00:24:34,919
to the point where he was almost losing consciousness.

487
00:24:34,919 --> 00:24:37,021
And he got the pressure low enough to where he could bend

488
00:24:37,021 --> 00:24:39,683
his body around and close the hatch, which is lucky because,

489
00:24:39,683 --> 00:24:42,926
in fact, the other cosmonaut was given orders that if he

490
00:24:42,926 --> 00:24:45,508
couldn't get back in, that he was to jettison the airlock

491
00:24:45,508 --> 00:24:47,490
with Alexei in it and come back safely himself.

492
00:24:47,490 --> 00:24:49,691
And, in fact, Alexei had a suicide pill with him in that

493
00:24:49,691 --> 00:24:50,292
case of that happening.

494
00:24:50,292 --> 00:24:52,394
But, at any rate, they did make it back in.

495
00:24:52,394 --> 00:24:55,176
And, you know, at that point, they were ready for reentry.

496
00:24:55,176 --> 00:24:58,539
And after they fired their reentry boosters, another

497
00:24:58,539 --> 00:24:59,940
problem happened where the

498
00:25:00,340 --> 00:25:02,422
this service module, this kind of back portion,

499
00:25:02,422 --> 00:25:03,223
didn't separate.

500
00:25:03,223 --> 00:25:05,384
The straps didn't come apart the way they were supposed to.

501
00:25:05,384 --> 00:25:06,285
So the dynamics of this,

502
00:25:06,285 --> 00:25:07,786
coming into the atmosphere, were totally backwards.

503
00:25:07,786 --> 00:25:10,368
And in fact, the hatch was facing downward,

504
00:25:10,368 --> 00:25:11,129
not the heat shield.

505
00:25:11,129 --> 00:25:12,990
And so they were starting to see smoke

506
00:25:12,990 --> 00:25:14,211
coming in through the hatch.

507
00:25:14,211 --> 00:25:15,052
The thing was rumbling.

508
00:25:15,052 --> 00:25:15,952
But around that time,

509
00:25:15,952 --> 00:25:17,914
the straps finally burned through,

510
00:25:17,914 --> 00:25:20,055
and it reoriented itself correctly

511
00:25:20,055 --> 00:25:21,316
just before the seals in the hatch blew.

512
00:25:21,316 --> 00:25:23,618
So they basically kind of made it through that.

513
00:25:23,618 --> 00:25:25,540
But that reentry profile was radically different,

514
00:25:25,540 --> 00:25:26,480
which means that they landed

515
00:25:26,480 --> 00:25:28,742
several hundred miles off course in the Ural Mountains.

516
00:25:29,288 --> 00:25:32,851
When the spaceship landed, it landed between two trees, actually jamming the hatch shut.

517
00:25:32,851 --> 00:25:35,473
They spent about an hour rocking the capsule back and forth.

518
00:25:35,473 --> 00:25:37,634
Nobody knew where they were at this point.

519
00:25:37,634 --> 00:25:40,637
But they managed to rock it out between these two trees enough to open the hatch,

520
00:25:40,637 --> 00:25:43,599
at which point, you know, it was getting dark, cold, it was, you know, very, very cold.

521
00:25:43,599 --> 00:25:44,820
They had to make a campfire.

522
00:25:44,820 --> 00:25:49,143
And then the wolves started closing in.

523
00:25:49,143 --> 00:25:53,526
But, luckily, a helicopter crew found them and dropped some paratroopers

524
00:25:53,526 --> 00:25:55,948
about ten hours later as daylight was breaking.

525
00:25:56,483 --> 00:26:00,705
And it was after that mission, every single Russian space flight after this,

526
00:26:00,705 --> 00:26:02,305
they give the cosmonauts guns and vodka.

527
00:26:02,305 --> 00:26:04,566
Just such an eventuality.

528
00:26:04,566 --> 00:26:08,567
And that was what really started that whole tradition.

529
00:26:08,567 --> 00:26:11,028
Alexei was also the commander of the Apollo-Soyuz test project

530
00:26:11,028 --> 00:26:12,388
and met the astronauts for the first time.

531
00:26:12,388 --> 00:26:15,909
This was the first time the Soviet cosmonauts actually met the American astronauts.

532
00:26:15,909 --> 00:26:18,190
And he said that when he met the American astronauts,

533
00:26:18,190 --> 00:26:21,051
it was amazing because the American astronauts were all 10 years older,

534
00:26:21,051 --> 00:26:23,311
college educated, with master's degrees,

535
00:26:23,311 --> 00:26:25,712
whereas the Russians were like these young yahoos out of the Air Force.

536
00:26:26,318 --> 00:26:29,760
And it was really a kind of, not just a cultural mismatch,

537
00:26:29,760 --> 00:26:31,862
but almost a generational mismatch as well.

538
00:26:31,862 --> 00:26:34,023
As I said, he was actually going to be,

539
00:26:34,023 --> 00:26:38,946
because of his EVA experience, the first cosmonaut on the moon,

540
00:26:38,946 --> 00:26:41,707
their lunar lander was actually designed to only land one person,

541
00:26:41,707 --> 00:26:44,909
and it required a fairly risky EVA even to get into it up in orbit.

542
00:26:44,909 --> 00:26:48,151
But the Soviets never perfected the N1, which is their giant moon booster.

543
00:26:48,151 --> 00:26:49,912
You know, they tried four test launches,

544
00:26:49,912 --> 00:26:52,513
every one exploded before going too far.

545
00:26:52,513 --> 00:26:55,935
In fact, it was the largest explosion, non-nuclear explosion, ever recorded.

546
00:26:56,322 --> 00:26:59,163
on Earth was the N1 booster blowing up on the launch pad.

547
00:26:59,163 --> 00:27:03,004
But Alexei also is a kind of interesting guy because he's an artist.

548
00:27:03,004 --> 00:27:06,366
He does fine art, he does space art, he does landscapes.

549
00:27:06,366 --> 00:27:08,846
And for a general in the Russian Air Force,

550
00:27:08,846 --> 00:27:12,688
he's kind of an amazingly interesting, well-rounded guy.

551
00:27:12,688 --> 00:27:15,349
The spaceship in 2010 was actually named after him, the Leonov.

552
00:27:15,349 --> 00:27:17,569
And I had the privilege to actually get to know him a bit.

553
00:27:17,569 --> 00:27:21,130
He actually came and stayed at my house for a week a few years ago.

554
00:27:21,130 --> 00:27:23,211
And he's just an amazing, spunky guy.

555
00:27:23,211 --> 00:27:26,152
And he is just the feistiest character you could ever imagine.

556
00:27:26,897 --> 00:27:37,883
But, anyway, that's the story of Alexei Leonov. Back to Bungling Bay.

557
00:27:37,883 --> 00:27:41,305
So now we have this world with resources being collected,

558
00:27:41,305 --> 00:27:44,947
airstrips, air defenses, et cetera, et cetera.

559
00:27:44,947 --> 00:27:50,450
Now one thing that I found, you know, after Bungling Bay was released, kind of in the spirit of a post-mortem,

560
00:27:50,450 --> 00:27:53,932
was that players totally got this repair priority. They kind of understood that,

561
00:27:53,932 --> 00:27:56,553
oh, I've got to get the guns fast. They're going to be rebuilt fast.

562
00:27:56,810 --> 00:28:00,713
that was totally transparent to the player. They had no idea about this resource flow

563
00:28:00,713 --> 00:28:04,956
thing. It was totally opaque to the players and pretty much wasted on people. They might

564
00:28:04,956 --> 00:28:09,059
have understood that these boats and tanks had something to do with it, but it was not

565
00:28:09,059 --> 00:28:13,021
clear at all what. Kind of thinking back on it, really I should have made the resources

566
00:28:13,021 --> 00:28:16,324
visible, because it was kind of a really stupid decision to make them invisible. I should

567
00:28:16,324 --> 00:28:19,386
have actually shown them out in the water with the ships picking them up, bringing them

568
00:28:19,386 --> 00:28:22,588
to the dock, having the tanks, bringing them to the factory, and actually seeing them converted.

569
00:28:22,986 --> 00:28:26,187
back into, you know, the components that they were rebuilding. I think that one change alone

570
00:28:26,187 --> 00:28:29,968
probably would have been the biggest improvement I can think of, looking back on it, that I

571
00:28:29,968 --> 00:28:34,750
would have made to Bungling Bay. Now, there was also kind of the difficulty level issue.

572
00:28:34,750 --> 00:28:38,491
I didn't want to have a game with discrete levels. I wanted to have a game that was one

573
00:28:38,491 --> 00:28:43,193
coherent world. So instead what I chose to do was that depending on how many factories

574
00:28:43,193 --> 00:28:48,374
you destroyed, the defenses within that world would escalate. With six factories, you had

575
00:28:48,374 --> 00:28:51,515
pretty simple defenses, you know, simple anti-aircraft and a little bit of light.

576
00:28:51,801 --> 00:28:55,584
ground fire from the boats and the tanks. Once you destroyed one factory, the first

577
00:28:55,584 --> 00:28:59,647
jets appeared. They would start chasing around, firing missiles at your helicopter. Once you

578
00:28:59,647 --> 00:29:03,569
got to the fourth factory, bombers would appear. These bombers would attack your aircraft carrier.

579
00:29:03,569 --> 00:29:07,592
Third one, they would actually escalate some of the attacks. By the time you got to the

580
00:29:07,592 --> 00:29:12,216
two factories left, guided missiles would appear. And this battleship would start accelerating

581
00:29:12,216 --> 00:29:15,658
its construction. So the idea was that, you know, as you got further and further in the

582
00:29:15,658 --> 00:29:19,781
game, the game was pushing back on you harder and harder with this very dynamic spring tension.

583
00:29:20,341 --> 00:29:23,382
And really the way I wanted to think about it was that, you know, I thought in the first

584
00:29:23,382 --> 00:29:27,184
game somebody should probably die before they've blown up one factory. By the second time they

585
00:29:27,184 --> 00:29:30,605
play the game they should get at least one factory. By maybe the fourth time they should

586
00:29:30,605 --> 00:29:34,607
get this far and so forth. So that by the time, you know, you got to the last factory

587
00:29:34,607 --> 00:29:38,048
you'd probably play the game, you know, 10, 15, 20 times to get that last one. And I think

588
00:29:38,048 --> 00:29:43,570
I pretty much achieved this pretty well. Because if you play Bungling Bay, it's that last factory

589
00:29:43,570 --> 00:29:46,812
that's like half the game really. You can get like four or five down.

590
00:29:47,266 --> 00:29:50,728
in a few minutes pretty easily, but when you get to the last one, it gets really intense

591
00:29:50,728 --> 00:29:57,692
and the escalation of tension is pretty interesting. I'm going to show you a little bit of a video

