00:47:37,846 --> 00:47:37,886
Hi.

926
00:47:37,886 --> 00:47:37,926
Hi.

927
00:47:37,926 --> 00:47:38,146
Hey, yeah.

928
00:47:38,146 --> 00:47:49,874
Yeah, I just wondered if you could share your thoughts on the N1 rocket platform and any

929
00:47:49,874 --> 00:47:55,277
of the issues there that may have kept them from successfully being able to get to the

930
00:47:55,277 --> 00:47:55,538
moon.

931
00:47:55,538 --> 00:47:55,938
Oh, the N1.

932
00:47:55,938 --> 00:47:56,118
Yeah.

933
00:47:56,118 --> 00:47:56,678
Yeah.

934
00:47:56,678 --> 00:47:56,798
Yeah.

935
00:47:57,348 --> 00:47:58,369
That's a long story.

936
00:47:58,369 --> 00:48:00,971
That's a whole other Russian Space Minute.

937
00:48:00,971 --> 00:48:02,552
The N1 was an amazing booster,

938
00:48:02,552 --> 00:48:04,674
and they had amazing engineers on it,

939
00:48:04,674 --> 00:48:06,035
but they didn't have the budget.

940
00:48:06,035 --> 00:48:07,657
The entire Russian space program,

941
00:48:07,657 --> 00:48:09,158
you know, even up to that point,

942
00:48:09,158 --> 00:48:11,520
up to, like, the lunar race,

943
00:48:11,520 --> 00:48:13,642
the Russians were basically operating

944
00:48:13,642 --> 00:48:15,803
on about 20% of the resources of NASA.

945
00:48:15,803 --> 00:48:18,125
The Saturn V did a huge number of ground tests

946
00:48:18,125 --> 00:48:19,387
of the Saturn V booster,

947
00:48:19,387 --> 00:48:20,868
and they had some huge problems

948
00:48:20,868 --> 00:48:22,169
with the internal dynamics of that,

949
00:48:22,169 --> 00:48:22,849
called pogoing,

950
00:48:22,849 --> 00:48:24,771
where these oscillations would start being set up

951
00:48:24,771 --> 00:48:26,032
and the thing would shake itself apart.

952
00:48:26,551 --> 00:48:28,473
And it was only because of their extensive ground testing

953
00:48:28,473 --> 00:48:30,454
that they were able to kind of solve that problem.

954
00:48:30,454 --> 00:48:32,996
You know, basically, had NASA had the budget the Russians did,

955
00:48:32,996 --> 00:48:34,718
there's no way the Saturn V would have ever,

956
00:48:34,718 --> 00:48:35,719
you know, become flight ready.

957
00:48:35,719 --> 00:48:37,881
So the Russians were forced to do flight tests

958
00:48:37,881 --> 00:48:39,222
when instead they should have been doing ground tests.

959
00:48:39,222 --> 00:48:40,883
And they were all full-scale tests

960
00:48:40,883 --> 00:48:42,485
of every stage at the same time.

961
00:48:42,485 --> 00:48:44,446
And that was the only way they possibly even had a shot at it.

962
00:48:44,446 --> 00:48:45,467
And they kind of knew that.

963
00:48:45,467 --> 00:48:46,988
They kind of knew that it was a long shot.

964
00:48:46,988 --> 00:48:48,690
They had about a one-in-three chance or maybe a one-in,

965
00:48:48,690 --> 00:48:50,912
you know, six chance of pulling it off.

966
00:48:50,912 --> 00:48:53,174
And the N1 was this humongous thing.

967
00:48:53,174 --> 00:48:54,315
It was bigger than the Saturn V.

968
00:48:55,367 --> 00:48:59,129
had a huge number of engines in the bottom of it.

969
00:48:59,129 --> 00:49:02,771
And also the material science in Russia was a little bit beyond NASA,

970
00:49:02,771 --> 00:49:05,832
and they kept having failures down in the turbine section of the engine,

971
00:49:05,832 --> 00:49:09,934
and typically most of the failures were the result of a turbine burst

972
00:49:09,934 --> 00:49:13,636
that would then cascade through the entire first stage.

973
00:49:13,636 --> 00:49:14,936
But that's the short story.

974
00:49:14,936 --> 00:49:16,797
Awesome, thank you.

975
00:49:16,797 --> 00:49:17,777
Sure.

976
00:49:17,777 --> 00:49:19,098
Yeah?

977
00:49:19,098 --> 00:49:22,780
Hey, I was at your IGDA interview with the Romero Archives.

978
00:49:23,167 --> 00:49:28,889
Yeah. And you talked about that robot kind of game that you were contemplating while you were developing SimCity kind of in parallel.

979
00:49:28,889 --> 00:49:31,109
Oh right, yeah. In fact, I kind of skipped over that here.

980
00:49:31,109 --> 00:49:37,872
But there was a game I worked on actually between Red Emberling Bay and SimCity that I called ProBot.

981
00:49:37,872 --> 00:49:42,653
And it was a very strange game. It was like, I was moving over a scrolling world still,

982
00:49:42,653 --> 00:49:46,715
but it was like this Escher-like world of platforms and catwalks and ramps.

983
00:49:46,715 --> 00:49:49,116
And in that world, you actually were driving this little robot.

984
00:49:49,116 --> 00:49:51,977
And basically, it was a little six-wheel robot with an arm on top.

985
00:49:52,553 --> 00:49:54,514
And if you move the joystick around, you would drive the robot.

986
00:49:54,514 --> 00:49:57,715
If you held the button down to move the joystick, you would move the arm.

987
00:49:57,715 --> 00:50:00,096
And so you could kind of move around, up and down these little platforms,

988
00:50:00,096 --> 00:50:01,456
and pick up things and manipulate them.

989
00:50:01,456 --> 00:50:05,657
And then on top of that, I built this kind of weird landscape of waterfalls,

990
00:50:05,657 --> 00:50:06,818
some going uphill, some going downhill.

991
00:50:06,818 --> 00:50:09,799
Again, you know, downhill, a very Escher-like world

992
00:50:09,799 --> 00:50:13,660
that little things were flowing on the water,

993
00:50:13,660 --> 00:50:15,740
little balls and boxes and pyramids and stuff.

994
00:50:15,740 --> 00:50:19,421
And you were trying to collect these, you know, with opponents.

995
00:50:19,421 --> 00:50:21,702
It's kind of hard to describe, but...

996
00:50:21,702 --> 00:50:21,842
Yes.

997
00:50:22,367 --> 00:50:27,590
So my question was, in that talk and in now, there's sort of this series of facts and it's

998
00:50:27,590 --> 00:50:31,032
this interesting hindsight model. I was wondering if you could talk about, you know, in the

999
00:50:31,032 --> 00:50:34,914
moment, like a lot of these people here, you're, you know, you don't know that SimCity is a

1000
00:50:34,914 --> 00:50:38,876
really great idea and that's going to succeed. Were there like emotions and sort of decision

1001
00:50:38,876 --> 00:50:43,078
making you had to do to, like hard decisions to go with SimCity? How did that feel in the

1002
00:50:43,078 --> 00:50:43,418
moment?

1003
00:50:43,418 --> 00:50:47,641
That's a good point. So I was working on this little robot game and kind of at the same

1004
00:50:47,641 --> 00:50:50,462
time I started playing around with the editor and playing around with SimCity.

1005
00:50:50,950 --> 00:50:54,733
It wasn't SimCity at that time, it was a world editor and I was putting down little roads.

1006
00:50:54,733 --> 00:50:58,115
But I began becoming interested in adding more dynamics to the world.

1007
00:50:58,115 --> 00:51:00,556
I wanted to see traffic moving on the roads and things happening.

1008
00:51:00,556 --> 00:51:04,359
And so that was the first time I actually started reading books on, you know, cities

1009
00:51:04,359 --> 00:51:08,081
and urban planning and urban dynamics and came across the work of Jay Forrester who

1010
00:51:08,081 --> 00:51:10,943
wrote a seminal work way back called Urban Dynamics.

1011
00:51:10,943 --> 00:51:18,247
And because I had that kind of resource, this depth of a whole field of topic to research,

1012
00:51:18,247 --> 00:51:19,148
I got interested.

1013
00:51:19,462 --> 00:51:20,682
more interested in this little program.

1014
00:51:20,682 --> 00:51:22,523
Hey, I wonder if I can do a traffic model

1015
00:51:22,523 --> 00:51:23,864
the way they do traffic models.

1016
00:51:23,864 --> 00:51:24,985
I wonder if I can do land value

1017
00:51:24,985 --> 00:51:26,766
according to this theory.

1018
00:51:26,766 --> 00:51:27,947
And in some sense,

1019
00:51:27,947 --> 00:51:29,608
the research I was uncovering

1020
00:51:29,608 --> 00:51:31,149
that eventually led me to SimCity

1021
00:51:31,149 --> 00:51:33,370
was encouraging me to spend more and more time

1022
00:51:33,370 --> 00:51:34,250
working on that simulator.

1023
00:51:34,250 --> 00:51:36,192
Whereas the robot game was really just this

1024
00:51:36,192 --> 00:51:36,992
fantasy little world.

1025
00:51:36,992 --> 00:51:38,313
It wasn't really connected to anything.

1026
00:51:38,313 --> 00:51:39,674
It was purely from my imagination,

1027
00:51:39,674 --> 00:51:41,195
which was cool in and of itself.

1028
00:51:41,195 --> 00:51:43,316
But I think there was something deeply fulfilling

1029
00:51:43,316 --> 00:51:45,457
about me trying to recreate the world

1030
00:51:45,457 --> 00:51:46,558
in what became SimCity.

1031
00:51:47,037 --> 00:51:49,297
relative to imagining just a fantasy world in the robot game.

1032
00:51:49,297 --> 00:51:51,758
And I think that's kind of what really tipped the balance.

1033
00:51:51,758 --> 00:51:53,438
That I found myself more and more...

1034
00:51:53,438 --> 00:51:56,939
I never really thought of city planning as that fascinating

1035
00:51:56,939 --> 00:51:57,660
until I had been...

1036
00:51:57,660 --> 00:52:00,921
At some point, popped up and realized I was developing a city simulator

1037
00:52:00,921 --> 00:52:01,921
for several months.

1038
00:52:01,921 --> 00:52:02,681
And I kind of looked back and said,

1039
00:52:02,681 --> 00:52:04,902
wow, this is like a little city simulator, isn't it?

1040
00:52:04,902 --> 00:52:07,823
And that was the point at which I started noticing urban books,

1041
00:52:07,823 --> 00:52:08,883
urban planning books, and saying,

1042
00:52:08,883 --> 00:52:09,823
wow, that looks like a good book.

1043
00:52:09,823 --> 00:52:11,384
Whereas before, I would have walked by and said,

1044
00:52:11,384 --> 00:52:12,744
wow, that sounds boring.

1045
00:52:12,744 --> 00:52:14,925
And it was this almost discovery, the fact that...

1046
00:52:15,757 --> 00:52:19,200
by having this little guinea pig city on my computer I could poke and prod

1047
00:52:19,200 --> 00:52:21,422
now made the subject matter fascinating to me.

1048
00:52:21,422 --> 00:52:25,204
Whereas before the subject matter, just reading it in text would have been very dry and boring.

1049
00:52:25,204 --> 00:52:29,187
So it was that discovery that I think I wanted the player to kind of re-experience

1050
00:52:29,187 --> 00:52:30,749
when they were playing the game.

1051
00:52:30,749 --> 00:52:33,831
So did you say the model was sort of following your own interests and fun

1052
00:52:33,831 --> 00:52:34,952
and just trusting your instincts?

1053
00:52:34,952 --> 00:52:39,515
Yeah. I mean, in that case, you know, typically almost all the games I've worked on,

1054
00:52:39,515 --> 00:52:43,258
every game I've worked on, has been, you know, some passion, some interest I've had.

1055
00:52:43,733 --> 00:52:52,200
that I knew that I could, you know, spend years immersed in this because I love the idea of the subject, the topic, whatever it is, whether it's ants or cities, astronomy or helicopters.

1056
00:52:52,200 --> 00:52:57,925
You know, unless you really enjoy, you know, the topic, you're not going to do a good job on it.

1057
00:52:57,925 --> 00:53:02,168
So, and to me, that was one of the huge attractions of becoming a game designer.

1058
00:53:02,168 --> 00:53:06,191
You know, it was when I realized that, that I realized, okay, I don't have to become an architect or an engineer or whatever.

1059
00:53:06,191 --> 00:53:10,835
If I'm a game designer, I can study whatever subject I want to, immerse myself in it, and get paid for it.

1060
00:53:11,142 --> 00:53:15,403
It was one of the few careers I actually saw where I could spend my life learning about

1061
00:53:15,403 --> 00:53:18,905
random disconnected topics and still making go of it.

